  "prompt": "Why isn't the Moon spinning?",
  "response": "The Moon is actually spinning, but it appears not to because of a phenomenon called \"synchronous rotation\" or \"tidal locking.\" This means that the time it takes for the Moon to rotate once on its axis is exactly the same as the time it takes to orbit the Earth, which is about 27.3 days. As a result, the same side of the Moon always faces Earth.\n\nTidal locking occurs because of gravitational interactions between the Earth and the Moon. Early in its history, the Moon spun at a different rate, but the gravitational forces caused by the Earth created tidal bulges. These bulges experienced friction that gradually slowed the Moon's rotation over millions of years until it reached synchronous rotation. This is why we always see the same side of the Moon from Earth.",
